Khemere
Ingredients
1 cup Granulated sugar 
1-1.5 tbsp grated fresh ginger
2 Liter of water
1/3 pack of yeast
Peel of 1 pineapple (optional)
Directions
Bring 1 liter of water to a rolling boil. Put sugar in boiling liter of water and stir until sugar is dissolved. Remove water from stove and add all the ginger and pineapple peel. Stir. Add liter of cold water to the pot. Let cool into mixture is lukewarm. Pour mixture into a container large enough- best if it is glass. Add yeast. Stir. Cover container but leave slightly ajar to allow for it to burp. Leave in a dark, room temp cabinet for at least 3 days to ferment. Check everyday after the first three days. You can keep “feeding” your khemere every other day with 1 tbsp of sugar. The longer you feed it the more it will ferment. I think it tastes best after 7-8 days. 
To serve, sieve the khemere and serve in a tall glass with ice. You can add thin wedges of the pineapple for aesthetics. 
#ginger #gingershot #cooking #aroundtheworld

There is place in Japan called Rabbit Island. This is located on Ōkunoshima, a small island in the Inland Sea of Japan. The island has a dark past. In 1925, the Imperial Japanese Army Institute of Science and Technology initiated a secret program to develop chemical weapons, In particular mustard and tear gas. The facotories have since shut down and now rabbits roam the land. Many of them are descended from rabbits intentionally let loose when the island was developed as a park after World War II. You can now visit the island play with the rabbits and visit the Poison Gas museum. 
How would you feel about visiting a bunny island? 

#rabbits #japan #okunoshima #bunny #bunnies

First up: Lençóis Maranhenses National Park, in Maranhão State. This is an ecosystem formed of white dunes that were formed thousands of years.
The seasonal lagoons fill up with rainwater, mostly during the first six months of the year, giving Lençóis Maranhenses its unique landscape. Mangroves, deserted beaches and the Preguiças River contribute to the park's biodiversity. 
100% bucket listed.

Images of the New York City subway from the late 1970s and 1980s. 
The subway's today look very different. In 1984 New York City Transit Authority began a five-year program to eradicate graffiti. The years between 1985 and 1989 became known as the "diehard" era. 
By mid-1986 the MTA and the NYCTA were winning their "war on graffiti", with the last graffitied train removed from service in 1989.

This is extreme gardening at @ntpowiscastle in Welshpool, Wales.

Pretty wild job, makes me wonder for the group: how do you feel about heights?

Curators at the Smithsonian pose with the collections they are in charge of. The Smithsonian in DC has the largest natural history collection in the world — over 147 million specimens are there. These collections help scientists answer some of the largest questions in the natural world, where did we come from? How is the earth changing? By looking at these large collections of the natural world over time, the scientists play a vital role in advancing scientific knowledge, addressing societal issues, and increasing scientific literacy.

The perfect summer snacks apparently do exit. This is Tong sui, it's a term for any sweet soup or custard served as a dessert typically at the end of a meal in Chinese cuisine. These have a history that dates back hundreds of years, they were eaten in the Imperial Court by ancient Chinese royals and nobles to help digestion. Over time the dish has evolved like these seen with sai mai lo aka mini tapioca pearls swimming in sweetened coconut milk; or even a fruity mango soup with bits of pomelo and sago. So yeah, 2 please. 

#tongsui #saimailo #dessert #chinesedessert

Another spot for #BerylBucketList: Grutas de Tolantongo natural hot springs in Hidalgo, Mexico. It's located about 4 hours from Mexico City by car. Hidalgo is one of the states in Mexico with the most indigenous language speakers, which is how Tolantongo got its name! Originally Tonaltonko in Nahuatl, which translates into “home where it feels warm,” local towns nearby began calling it Tonaltongo. In 1975, a Mexican magazine misprinted the name as “Tolantongo,” and the hot springs retains that name today. The pools themselves are man made, however the volcanic heat source is natural. Seems like a cool trip to learn about a city and also spend a day in some hot springs. Daily admission to Grutas Tolantongo is 150 pesos ($7.39 USD) per person.
Has anyone been?

#mexico #hotspring #Tolantongo

While searching "meals on the titanic" as one does, I found a few spots that have curated evenings dedicated to dining as those did in first class on the day the Titanic sank. At @rayannehouse in Belfast they have an entire Titanic menu (all photos are from there) its 270 Euro for a room and dinner for 2. 
However, I found a wild little moment from a few years ago: At Hong Kong's luxury Hullett House hotel, for $1,930 per person — they recreated the evening of the final day and included a bottle of Heidsieck & Co Monopole Gout Americain vintage 1907, "brought up from the frigid depths of the Atlantic in pristine condition in 1998 and purchased by the luxury hotel for more than $11,000."

Would you want to do something like this?

#titanic #lastmeal

These are konnyaku jelly balls. Konnyaku is made from a root vegetable called konjac. When konjac powder is mixed with water it becomes gelatin-like. However, this type of jelly is firmer than your typical gelatin. In Japan, it's used in both sweet and savory dishes, you can find konjac noodles, konjac jelly in ramen, even vegan sashimi made with it! Summer fruit jellies are super common and if you go to any Japanese grocery store you can find them in squeezable pouches. Those are great, but looking at these, ooph,  I love the look of these perfect shimmering orbs! 

#konjac #japanesedessert #konnyakujelly #fruitjelly #japan

The Tamago sando is a Japanese style egg salad sandwich. A common convenience store item, these are traditionally made with Japanese mayonnaise and scrambled eggs or mashed hard-boiled eggs. Seasoned with salt and sugar, it's served on fluffy white buttered bread with the crusts cut off. 

If you're going to Japan, you have to get one from a konbini (convenience store) . FamilyMart offers the cheapest egg sandwich. 7-Eleven is the most expensive it's also the largest on the market. Lawson egg sandwiches is considered the best by many due to the egg filling to bread ratio. Just in case any of you are headed there soon. 

#tamago #eggsanwich #tamagosando #konbini #japanesesandwich #japan

This honey has hallucinogenic qualities. This is called mad honey, The pollen of certain rhododendron flowers contains grayanotoxin, which can cause physiological reactions in humans and animals. Everything from paralysis to hallucinations and ever unconsciousness.

Since the 1990's on Marajo, a small island off the Northern coast of Brazil, the military patrol the area mounted on water buffalo. 
The Asian water buffalo was introduced in Brazil in in the late nineteenth century. Today the country has one of the largest populations in the world, most of it in the Amazon basin. 
Per the New York Times, "The buffalo unit started in the 1990s, patrolling the sleepy outpost of Soure, which has about 23,000 people, and breaking up the occasional bar fight. Over the years, the mission has expanded to include pursuing suspects who flee into Marajó’s wilds and cracking down on buffalo rustling on the island’s far-reaching ranches."

These photos were taken by Fernando Camara.

One of them is this 65-foot (20-meter) long, complete skeleton of a legged kind of whale. In area known as Wadi Al-Hitan, often known as the Valley of the Whales, was formerly covered by a vast prehistoric ocean, but it has since disappeared as a result of falling sea levels and shifting landmasses.

These are the teeth of the crabeater seal. The seals live in Antarctica and have the most specialized teeth in the carnivore world.

You might think, ahh the better for eating crab with....well, think again. Crabeater seals do not eat crab. The interlocking teeth act as a sieve, allowing them to filter krill from the water. 

#teeth #nature #animals

This is a bagworm moth, and yes, it's carrying around it's own protective log cabin. When the moth is still a caterpillar, as seen in these photos, it's vulnerable, so to make its life as a larva safe and protected from predators, the caterpillar makes a silk cocoon and reinforces it with pieces of twigs, leaves and other plant matter. As the caterpillar hunts for food, it carries the "cabin" along with it wherever it goes. As the bagworm grows, it expands its case by adding more twigs to the top.

#bagworm #lepidoptera #moth #nature #logcabin

Today, I learned about a firefly lottery. Synchronous fireflies are one of at least 19 species of fireflies that live in Great Smoky Mountains National Park and one of only a few species in the world known to synchronize their flash patterns.

Every year, around late April, the National Park Service at Great Smoky Mountains National Park announces the dates for the lottery to view the synchronous firefly event. In previous years, the park received 22,000 applications for the coveted 1,800 parking passes. The event happend this past June but you might wanna mark your calendar for next year. 

Would you want to camp to see this event?

Imagine going to dig in the garden and finding a wooly mammoth skull. In 2015 , James Bristle and a friend were digging in his southern Michigan soybean field when they unearthed what looked like a bent fence post, caked with mud. Instead, it was part of a pelvis from an ancient woolly mammoth that lived up to 15,000 years ago. A team of paleontologists from the University of Michigan came to help and aside from the pelvis, they found the skull and two tusks, along with numerous vertebrae, ribs and both shoulder blades. So rad.

Locations:

2.Mercado Cuauhtémoc. Chicharrón. Location: Near the corner of Rio Tigris and Rio Lerma.

3.Quesadilla. Handmade corn tortillas filled with huitlacoche. Location: On the corner of Rio Lerma and Rio Sena.

4.Cemitas. Piled-high sandwiches with quesillo, avocado and chipotle. Location: Rio Sena between Rio Lerma & Reforma.

5.Carnitas. Slowly cooked pork topped with onion, cilantro and salsa. Location: Rio Sena between Rio Lerma & Reforma.

6.Pambazo. A crunchy sandwich filled with chorizo and potatoes, made with bread slathered in a chile sauce and crisped on a comal. Located near the corner of Niza and Liverpool.

7.Burrito. Location: On Liverpool between Niza & Havre.

8. Bean to bar Mexican chocolate. La Rifa Chocolatería. Location: Dinamarca 47, Cuauhtémoc.

This is my favorite way to have grilled cheese right now. 
With holiday cooking and all the craziness, I’ve been doing a lot of “easy meals” and this keeps on hitting the spot. 
It’s my cinnamon apple with New Zealand honey and chili crisp grilled cheddar sandwich, plus an alcohol free Gin and Tonic that I am LOVING. 

Recipe:
Sautee your apples in butter with a little cinnamon, when they are soft remove them from the pan. 
Butter your bread and add sliced sharp cheddar, your stewed apples and on the other slice of bread spread your honey and add chili crisp. Top with a little more cheese and cover the sandwich. Add a peeled garlic clove into the pan before covering it and let it cook on low heat. 
When you’ve reached peak crispy and cheese meltiness, remove the sandwich, rub the toasted bread with your now soft garlic and enjoy! 

I worked with Made with Care to create this, it is New Zealand’s initiative to connect consumers around the world with premium food and beverage options and natural ingredients from the country.
Be sure to check out http://nzmadewithcare.com/us for more incredible products from New Zealand like the honey, apples, butter and drink I used!

#NZMadeWithCare, #ad, @discovernew.nz @thekiwifeel #grilledcheese

Chickpeas play a major role in Indian dishes because many traditional delicacies include them either in their base or as an addition to something else. Trinidadian doubles are the most famous street food specific to the region. The dish includes two soft fried doughs, later topped with chickpeas. The recipe for doubles was brought to me by Annesha from Trinidad and Tobago, who introduced this delicacy as a must-try. Besides being easy to prepare, the doubles are known as comfort food that can be eaten at any time of the day. 

The full recipe is here: https://www.beryl.nyc/index.php/2023/11/30/doubles/

If you love chickpeas and tofu, now it’s the time to try something unique! Burmese tofu nway is a classic breakfast dish in Myanmar in which soybeans are replaced by chickpea flour. When Ivy from Yangon shared this recipe, she pointed out that this delicious delicacy genuinely represents her country’s food. It is considered a traditional breakfast in every Burmese household, so it’s absolutely worth trying. 

This dish is like a flavor party in your mouth! First up, you’ve got the chickpea paste, giving it that creamy goodness. Then, there are the rice noodles to hold everything together. And let’s not forget the show’s star – the chicken curry, bringing the savory vibes. Once the three components are ready, you top it off with a splash of soy sauce, some crushed peanuts for that satisfying crunch, and a pinch of fried garlic or onion to keep things spicy and interesting. 

The full recipe is here: https://www.beryl.nyc/index.php/2023/11/30/tofu-nway/

#chickpeas #burmesefood #tofu #myanmar

Mac & Cheese is an American classic, I’d be remiss to not include it in my roundup of recipes from around the world! This recipe comes to us courtesy of Nakia, who is currently living in Seattle, Washington in the United States. For Nakia, baked macaroni and cheese is closely tied with happy childhood memories. Nakia’s grandmother was known for her recipe and always prepared a batch for holidays, birthdays, special occasions, or any time the family needed something comforting. The recipe came out so delicious, I threw in a bit of Pepperjack for an extra spicy punch! 

Her recipe is here: https://www.beryl.nyc/index.php/2023/11/16/baked-mac-cheese/

Käsespätzle is special. Pasta, cheese and camamelized onions get baked together and become something truly incredinle. I ended up making this for my family for Thanksgiving after the full length episode come out! 
In German, “Käse” simply means “cheese,” so Käsespätzle roughly translates to “cheese noodles.” This particular recipe for Käsespätzle comes to us from Lea, who is from Berlin, Germany. According to Lea, this noodle dish is a deeply integral part of German culture. Even though it can be found in a few restaurants, Lea says that Käsespätzle is often thought of as a home cooked dish that places an emphasis on shared, communal cooking. 

The full recipe can be found here: https://www.beryl.nyc/index.php/2023/11/16/kasespatzle/

#macandcheese #germany #germanfood #easyrecipes #familydinnerideas

If you love dishes with chickpeas, then you absolutely have to try Lebanese chickpeas fatteh. This delightful recipe came to me from Yasmina from Lebanon. She was kind enough to share this glorious traditional delight from her country, and I fell in love with it at the first bite! You can prepare it in several ways, and it can easily be your go-to instant dish when you don’t have a lot of time for cooking.

Curry lovers will surely love Pakistani chikar cholay because it offers an amazing blend of flavors and spices that create magic in your mouth. The dish includes chickpeas simmered in spices, and at first, it may seem like just any other chickpea recipe. However, chikar cholay comes with a twist – a black tea infusion that brings delightful flavors and makes it truly special. 

According to Arooba, Pakistani chikar cholay is the VIP meal in special gatherings in her country. Her parents and grandparents passed down the sacred art of making it, so now, she can do it herself. As she says, it’s a magical dish that brings people together, and as soon as I tasted it, her statement was clear as day.

Have you ever heard of Hungarian Túrós Tészta?
